Happiest when I’m hiking 🥾 

📍Devils Bridge, Sedona AZ

*** Save for later***

Devils Bridge in Sedona is an easy trail to hike with one short section of rock scrambling. The hike has beautiful red rock scenery and of course, the chance to walk on the famous Devils Bridge arch. This hike makes the top of the list for many who visit Sedona and is one of the most popular trails so be prepared for crowds if you want to walk and have photos taken on top of the iconic red rock arch.

You have four options for starting this hike:

*Dry Creek Rd to Devils Bridge trailhead
(You must have a high clearance 4x4)
*Park at Dry Creek Rd parking lot
*Avoid driving by taking the Sedona shuttle to the Dry Creek parking lot (shuttles are free)
*Park at the Mescal trailhead

Distance - 2 miles with a 4x4 and 4.2 miles without a 4x4
Length - 1-3 hrs
Elevation - 400 to 500 feet
Difficulty - easy with one section of rock scrambling

🥾 Happy hiking! ✌🏾

📍Cathedral Gorge State Park, NV.

Save for your trip ⬇️

Cathedral Gorge State Park - located just a 2.5 hour drive from Las Vegas is one of Nevada’s first state parks.

Volcanoes, earthquakes, water, and erosion created the spires and buff-colored cliffs. Modern day erosion continues to sculpt the formation and deeply incised canyons.

Cathedral Gorge features hiking trails, campgrounds, picnic areas and a visitor center. Group camping areas accommodate day or night groups and facilities include large shade ramadas, grills, picnic tables, water and restrooms with flush toilets and hot showers 🙌🏿

📍Big Falls Trail, Mt. Charleston, NV.

A hidden seasonal waterfall! Big Falls is a trail that ends with, well, a big waterfall as the name would say and it could very well be the most impressive of the waterfalls in the Mt. Charleston area and Las Vegas vicinity.

While most people have heard of Mary Jane Falls, which happens to share a trail with Big Falls. Given that the trails share the same path, make sure to take a left turn once you reach the break off for the two trails. Its unfortunately not marked but there’s a 20ft + log that has been there for as long as I have been hiking Mt. Charleston. Making a right turn will take you to Mary Jane Falls switchbacks.

Distance - 4 miles +/- round trip

Elevation Gain - 1500ft

Difficulty- fairly difficult but it all depends on how well you can handle elevation and rock scrambling on a steep trail.

Trail Conditions- lots of large boulders and rocks, steep trail.

I have hiked this trail once in March several years ago and there was not a single drop and there was no snow. This time around, there’s about 10 ft of snow. So, be sure to adjust based on weather conditions of that day.

If this is a trail you plan on hiking soon then I highly recommend hiking poles, clamp ons for your boots, and waterproof hiking boots.

Happy hiking! 🙌🏿

Something to do when in Boulder City.

📍Historic Railroad Pass, Boulder City, NV.

Enjoy this gravel trail which offers panoramic views along the shorelines of Lake Mead and it’s only a 40 minute drive from the Las Vegas Strip.

The trail offers spectacular views of Lake Mead through the five railroad tunnels towards Hoover Dam. 

This trail is wheelchair/child stroller accessible as well as pet friendly. 

Fun fact: After the construction of Hoover Dam in 1935, the railroad ceased operation, and in 1962, the tracks were removed and the trail opened in 1995.

There’s free parking at the trailhead next to the Alan Bible Visitor Center.
